prompt_sent:
You are the Summariser skill. You take a long input and produce a short
form that preserves the load-bearing content.

You make no tool calls. The input arrives in the prompt under INPUTS.

Procedure:
  1. Read the input.
  2. Identify the load-bearing claims (the facts, dates, names, numbers
     a downstream reader would have to know).
  3. Emit a short summary that preserves them. Aim for 4–8 sentences for
     a paper-length input; one paragraph for a single-page input.

Output schema (JSON, no prose, no markdown fences):

  {
    "summary": "<the short summary>",
    "preserved_facts": ["<fact 1>", "<fact 2>", ...]
  }

`preserved_facts` is a short bullet list of the specific items you kept,
so a downstream Critic can check none were dropped silently.

USER_QUERY: Research the CMS Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program penalties. Summarize in exactly 4 bullets. Each bullet must be a single sentence containing NO commas. The critic must verify zero commas appear in any bullet.

INPUTS:
[
  {
    "id": "n:2",
    "kind": "upstream",
    "skill": "researcher",
    "output": {
      "question": "Research the CMS Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program penalties",
      "sources": [
        {
          "url": "https://www.cms.gov/medicare/quality/value-based-programs/hospital-readmissions",
          "title": "Hosp. Readmission Reduction | CMS"
        },
        {
          "url": "https://legalclarity.org/hospital-readmissions-reduction-program-how-penalties-work/",
          "title": "Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program: How Penalties Work"
        }
      ],
      "findings": "The Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program is a Medicare value-based purchasing program established by the Affordable Care Act that began reducing payments to hospitals in fiscal year 2013. The program applies to general short-term acute care hospitals paid under Medicare's Inpatient Prospective Payment System and excludes critical access hospitals long-term care hospitals rehabilitation facilities psychiatric hospitals and children's hospitals.\n\nPenalties are calculated using an Excess Readmission Ratio (ERR) that compares a hospital's predicted readmission rate to the expected rate for similar patients at an average hospital. Hospitals with ERRs above 1.0 face payment reductions of up to 3% of their total Medicare base operating payments while those at or below 1.0 receive no penalty. The program tracks six specific conditions: acute myocardial infarction chronic obstructive pulmonary disease heart failure pneumonia coronary artery bypass graft surgery and elective primary total hip or knee replacement.\n\nFor fiscal year 2026 approximately 78% of eligible hospitals face some level of penalty with about 240 hospitals losing at least 1% of their Medicare payments. The performance period for FY 2026 penalties covers discharges from July 1 2021 through June 30 2024 representing a three-year data window. Beginning with FY 2027 CMS will shorten this measurement window to two years making recent performance carry more weight in penalty calculations.\n\nThe program includes risk adjustment for patient complexity and peer group stratification to account for hospitals serving different populations particularly safety-net hospitals with higher proportions of low-income patients. Planned readmissions are excluded from calculations using CMS's Planned Readmission Algorithm and the 30-day readmission window captures unplanned returns to any acute care hospital regardless of the principal diagnosis."
    }
  }
]
